Asia market comment

Risk tone is turning cautious into the weekend, with a heavy macro calendar and oil-driven uncertainty keeping investors on the defensive.

Asian equities were mixed to weaker, setting a soft lead for Europe, while crude remains elevated around $105–106, reinforcing stagflation concerns. The focus is already shifting to next week’s central bank “super week,” where the Fed, ECB and BOJ are all expected on hold but with messaging skewed toward uncertainty and inflation risks tied to the Middle East shock.

Rates markets are reflecting that shift. Curves continue to flatten as front-end yields stay supported by inflation risk while longer-end demand builds on growth concerns. Supply dynamics (heavy front-end issuance) are reinforcing the flattening bias near term, although the medium-term steepening narrative remains alive if policy easing returns later in the cycle.

FX and EM highlight the same theme: oil is dominating. High-yielding Asian currencies are no longer protected by carry, with the Philippine peso a clear example of how energy shocks can overwhelm yield advantage and expose external imbalances. This dynamic is increasingly relevant across importers in the region. Long US dollar still seems the way to go and probably the next trade to hurt a market that might be once again wrongfooted .

Equities remain bifurcated. AI and semiconductors continue to power ahead — with Taiwan and Korea leading gains — but broader market breadth is weak and increasingly fragile. The rally is narrow, positioning is crowded, and sensitivity to oil and geopolitics is rising. Without clarity on the Strait of Hormuz, it’s hard to see a clean next leg higher.

Under the surface, funding markets also warrant attention, with early signs of stress emerging despite calm headline conditions — another reminder that liquidity risks haven’t disappeared.

Bottom line: markets are caught between a resilient AI-driven earnings story and a deteriorating macro backdrop shaped by oil, geopolitics and stagflation risk. Into next week’s central bank meetings, the bias is toward caution, flatter curves and more fragile risk appetite.
